00:36:09.596 --> 00:36:11.353
Isn't that a kind of
contradiction of terms?

00:36:11.353 --> 00:36:13.572
You mean they found one?

00:36:13.572 --> 00:36:15.033
(audience laughs)

00:36:15.033 --> 00:36:16.988
And there's like a book a month

00:36:16.988 --> 00:36:20.085
that sort of piles on in
these unflattering portrayals.

00:36:20.085 --> 00:36:22.182
The Primal Teen, that's
actually not too bad,

00:36:22.182 --> 00:36:24.376
but Mom, I Hate You: Get Out of My Life,

00:36:24.376 --> 00:36:27.306
but First, Drop Cheryl
and I Off At the Mall,

00:36:27.306 --> 00:36:28.914
Now, I Know Why Tigers Eat Their Young,

00:36:28.914 --> 00:36:32.298
or right to the point,
Yes, Your Teen is Crazy.

00:36:32.298 --> 00:36:34.989
But with the technologies such as

00:36:34.989 --> 00:36:38.360
magnetic resonance imaging,
we can for the first time

00:36:38.360 --> 00:36:41.344
look under the hood at
the living growing brain.

00:36:41.344 --> 00:36:46.260
And what we've found is that
not only do teens have brains,

00:36:46.260 --> 00:36:47.093
(audience laughs)

00:36:47.093 --> 00:36:49.752
but they're good brains.

00:36:49.752 --> 00:36:51.919
They're as they should be.

00:36:52.826 --> 00:36:54.539
They're not broken.

00:36:54.539 --> 00:36:57.510
And I'd go so far as to
say if they weren't the way

00:36:57.510 --> 00:37:01.625
that they are, we wouldn't even be here.

00:37:01.625 --> 00:37:06.317
Evidence from that comes from
a kind of unlikely source

00:37:06.317 --> 00:37:07.507
that I'll get to in a minute.

00:37:07.507 --> 00:37:11.043
So the teen brain's different
than the brain of a child.

00:37:11.043 --> 00:37:12.480
It's different than the brain of an adult.

00:37:12.480 --> 00:37:13.771
It's not just halfway between.

00:37:13.771 --> 00:37:18.325
It's, you know, kind of
its own distinct entity,

00:37:18.325 --> 00:37:20.906
and it's been exquisitely
forged by evolution

00:37:20.906 --> 00:37:22.629
to have certain features.

00:37:22.629 --> 00:37:26.796
Behaviorally, the big three
are increased risk taking,

00:37:27.672 --> 00:37:30.626
increased sensation
seeking, and a move away

00:37:30.626 --> 00:37:32.203
from parents to peers.

00:37:32.203 --> 00:37:34.245
And I think these are really deeply rooted

00:37:34.245 --> 00:37:35.748
in our biology cause it's not just humans.

00:37:35.748 --> 00:37:38.758
All social mammals have
these three features.

00:37:38.758 --> 00:37:41.175
And so, we're probably
fighting mother nature

00:37:41.175 --> 00:37:43.559
by trying to eliminate these.

00:37:43.559 --> 00:37:47.985
And this is always very
speculative to argue these ways,

00:37:47.985 --> 00:37:52.152
but one idea is that it
helped us get out of the home,

00:37:53.183 --> 00:37:55.926
which is a really irrational
thing to do, right?

00:37:55.926 --> 00:37:56.910
(audience laughs)

00:37:56.910 --> 00:37:57.743
People love us.

00:37:57.743 --> 00:37:58.576
They feed us.

00:37:58.576 --> 00:37:59.409
They protect us.

00:37:59.409 --> 00:38:00.672
It's a good gig, right?

00:38:00.672 --> 00:38:03.676
But it turns out it works better if we do.

00:38:03.676 --> 00:38:07.640
Less inbreeding, it just
sort of, not morally right

00:38:07.640 --> 00:38:12.126
or wrong, it just works
better if this happens.

00:38:12.126 --> 00:38:14.963
And so these features,
they evolved at a time

00:38:14.963 --> 00:38:17.999
without firearms, without,
you know, high speed

00:38:17.999 --> 00:38:20.176
motor vehicles, without
designer drugs and stuff.

00:38:20.176 --> 00:38:23.451
Some of these issues are
kind of the stone-age brain

00:38:23.451 --> 00:38:26.310
in a computer age world aspect.

00:38:26.310 --> 00:38:30.477
But I think that these
behaviors have virtues as well.

00:38:31.892 --> 00:38:35.877
When I was I was a the
NIH, the Smithsonian Museum

00:38:35.877 --> 00:38:36.710
was sort of close.

00:38:36.710 --> 00:38:38.949
They had this exhibit,
The Hall of Human Origins,

00:38:38.949 --> 00:38:43.264
which I really like, but kind
of not particularly featured.

00:38:43.264 --> 00:38:45.817
A little placard on the floor
looked at the relationship

00:38:45.817 --> 00:38:48.925
between brain size and climate change.

00:38:48.925 --> 00:38:51.209
And the last big increase in brain size,

00:38:51.209 --> 00:38:54.338
500, 800,000 years ago, but
what I thought was intriguing

00:38:54.338 --> 00:38:58.055
was that what would correlate
is the change in climate,

00:38:58.055 --> 00:39:00.089
not the degree.

00:39:00.089 --> 00:39:01.979
So before seeing this, I thought,
yeah, it got really cold.

00:39:01.979 --> 00:39:03.769
You had to be super
smart just to stay alive

00:39:03.769 --> 00:39:06.532
long enough to get food and reproduce.

00:39:06.532 --> 00:39:08.170
But this is subtly different.

00:39:08.170 --> 00:39:11.701
Everybody in this room
had ancestors whose brains

00:39:11.701 --> 00:39:13.701
were good at adaptation.

00:39:15.351 --> 00:39:18.758
And were really good at it in terms of,

00:39:18.758 --> 00:39:22.554
even compared to our quite
close, genetically close,

00:39:22.554 --> 00:39:25.868
rather in the Neandertrumps
or Neanderthals.

00:39:25.868 --> 00:39:28.679
(audience laughs)

00:39:28.679 --> 00:39:29.512
I'll pause.

00:39:29.512 --> 00:39:31.665
We can edit that later.

00:39:31.665 --> 00:39:34.546
(audience applauds)

00:39:34.546 --> 00:39:39.037
And there's a, we can tell
an enormous amount from teeth

00:39:39.037 --> 00:39:41.105
and fossilized teeth, which
is actually redundant.

00:39:41.105 --> 00:39:43.351
Everybody's teeth right now are fossils,

00:39:43.351 --> 00:39:47.635
calcified cells, but they work like trees.

00:39:47.635 --> 00:39:49.032
So they have rings.

00:39:49.032 --> 00:39:51.481
So tree rings you can,
this was a wet year,

00:39:51.481 --> 00:39:53.790
a good year of growth,
the rings are wider.

00:39:53.790 --> 00:39:56.427
And across many different
species, the rings

00:39:56.427 --> 00:39:58.919
get closer and closer as you mature.

00:39:58.919 --> 00:40:02.938
The rings stop, and you're
done growing, done maturing.

00:40:02.938 --> 00:40:06.188
And so when you find
these fossilized teeth,

00:40:06.188 --> 00:40:10.627
if you find a fossilized
Neanderthal tooth of a 12-year-old,

00:40:10.627 --> 00:40:12.161
and then check the rest
of the cave, he's gonna be

00:40:12.161 --> 00:40:14.708
with his children, not his parents.

00:40:14.708 --> 00:40:18.599
And this is often portrayed
as surprisingly rapid growth

00:40:18.599 --> 00:40:21.182
in the Neanderthals, but I
think that's the wrong way

00:40:21.182 --> 00:40:22.015
to look at it.

00:40:22.015 --> 00:40:25.732
What's surprising is
our protracted growth.

00:40:25.732 --> 00:40:27.940
We're the outliers by far.

00:40:27.940 --> 00:40:30.283
It's one of the most
distinctive things about us.

00:40:30.283 --> 00:40:34.450
And even across, like, crows
and many other species,

00:40:35.511 --> 00:40:38.085
the longer you're under
protection of your parent,

00:40:38.085 --> 00:40:40.511
the more complicated your food gathering,

00:40:40.511 --> 00:40:42.481
your communication, you
know, problem solving.

00:40:42.481 --> 00:40:44.748
Crows are actually really
smart as an example,

00:40:44.748 --> 00:40:49.425
but similar crows in size
and stuff that don't have

00:40:49.425 --> 00:40:51.986
this protective maturation
don't have those abilities

00:40:51.986 --> 00:40:53.169
as well.

00:40:53.169 --> 00:40:55.126
And it doesn't work to
just keep your kids at home

00:40:55.126 --> 00:40:56.088
'til they're 40.

00:40:56.088 --> 00:40:58.070
I don't think on an individual
basis it doesn't work.

00:40:58.070 --> 00:41:00.612
It's an intriguing trade-off I think

00:41:00.612 --> 00:41:02.417
that we keep options open.

00:41:02.417 --> 00:41:05.514
We keep our brains changeable,
see what the environment's

00:41:05.514 --> 00:41:06.347
gonna to be like.

00:41:06.347 --> 00:41:07.180
We can live on the North Pole.

00:41:07.180 --> 00:41:08.611
We can live on the Equator.

00:41:08.611 --> 00:41:10.507
We can even live in outer
space for a little while

00:41:10.507 --> 00:41:12.843
with technologies that are
being made and developed.

00:41:12.843 --> 00:41:15.336
And so this is a good
thing, I think, in terms

00:41:15.336 --> 00:41:20.243
of this ability to keep
options open for a long time,

00:41:20.243 --> 00:41:22.245
but it's really being put to the test

00:41:22.245 --> 00:41:24.578
with the digital revolution.

00:41:25.746 --> 00:41:29.913
And this is just in my short
career, it's a game-changer.

00:41:31.271 --> 00:41:34.267
In the way that we interact
and like we're doing

00:41:34.267 --> 00:41:37.555
at this moment with ones
and zeros and the lights,

00:41:37.555 --> 00:41:40.941
the projectors, you know,
it's changed everything.

00:41:40.941 --> 00:41:43.858
It's changed the way that we learn.

00:41:47.227 --> 00:41:49.039
You know, content that's on internet.

00:41:49.039 --> 00:41:51.717
I mean, the greatest minds on
the planet are a click away,

00:41:51.717 --> 00:41:53.044
for free.

00:41:53.044 --> 00:41:54.272
It's amazing.

00:41:54.272 --> 00:41:55.527
It's magical.

00:41:55.527 --> 00:41:58.273
The way that we play, and
the way that we interact

00:41:58.273 --> 00:42:00.090
with each other.

00:42:00.090 --> 00:42:03.538
And so, I've been fascinated
by this interaction

00:42:03.538 --> 00:42:07.961
in terms of the, you know,
biology of this changeability

00:42:07.961 --> 00:42:12.128
and the technologies that
have taken over, in a sense,

00:42:14.000 --> 00:42:17.606
so of almost 11 hours
a day of screen time.

00:42:17.606 --> 00:42:20.915
And 30% of that time more than one device.

00:42:20.915 --> 00:42:24.705
And so the usual question
is is it good or bad?

00:42:24.705 --> 00:42:26.433
That's the wrong question, right?

00:42:26.433 --> 00:42:30.785
Almost any interesting
question is it depends

00:42:30.785 --> 00:42:34.132
in terms of in what
ways and how it depends

00:42:34.132 --> 00:42:35.499
and what it depends upon.

00:42:35.499 --> 00:42:39.035
But I think that this is
an opportunity in terms

00:42:39.035 --> 00:42:41.368
of to influence adolescence.

00:42:43.011 --> 00:42:46.593
One of the tragedies of my profession

00:42:46.593 --> 00:42:48.625
is that it's almost a 10 year gap

00:42:48.625 --> 00:42:51.904
between onset of illness and treatment.

00:42:51.904 --> 00:42:56.458
It's, we need to do
better, and I think perhaps

00:42:56.458 --> 00:43:00.164
new technologies can help
us get there in terms of

00:43:00.164 --> 00:43:03.511
by monitoring things like
social media activity.

00:43:03.511 --> 00:43:06.486
Maybe even just movement
to best aid harnessing

00:43:06.486 --> 00:43:09.151
these technologies in an
ethically appropriate way

00:43:09.151 --> 00:43:12.504
to help us recognize mental
illness so that we can

00:43:12.504 --> 00:43:16.592
intervene while the brain
is still more changeable.

00:43:16.592 --> 00:43:19.603
And so a lot of the debates around this

00:43:19.603 --> 00:43:22.436
that it's just not natural, right.

00:43:23.840 --> 00:43:27.082
We evolve to talk to each
other, to be with each other,

00:43:27.082 --> 00:43:29.067
share smells and touches and everything.

00:43:29.067 --> 00:43:33.234
And now, we're looking at screens
for a big part of the day.

00:43:34.174 --> 00:43:35.522
But a kind of argument to that is

00:43:35.522 --> 00:43:38.159
reading's not natural either.

00:43:38.159 --> 00:43:41.222
Reading's only about 5,200 years old.

00:43:41.222 --> 00:43:43.815
So most humanity, nobody read.

00:43:43.815 --> 00:43:46.711
So I don't think that by
itself is a good argument.

00:43:46.711 --> 00:43:50.572
It kind of makes the point that the whole

00:43:50.572 --> 00:43:53.529
aspect of this is the changeability.

00:43:53.529 --> 00:43:55.706
10,000 years ago, hunting,
gathering berries,

00:43:55.706 --> 00:43:57.682
that's the same brain in terms of

00:43:57.682 --> 00:43:59.879
that's a blink of an eye
in evolutionary terms.

00:43:59.879 --> 00:44:01.994
But our brains are amazing.

00:44:01.994 --> 00:44:02.987
We can adapt.

00:44:02.987 --> 00:44:06.956
A lot of us spend a lot
of our day with symbols,

00:44:06.956 --> 00:44:09.168
you know, words, and that,

00:44:09.168 --> 00:44:10.910
and that's so different than, you know,

00:44:10.910 --> 00:44:13.384
what our ancestors did.

00:44:13.384 --> 00:44:16.782
And so my career has basically been this

00:44:16.782 --> 00:44:20.289
in terms of trying to
understand this plasticity

00:44:20.289 --> 00:44:23.283
in terms of how to optimize the good

00:44:23.283 --> 00:44:25.033
and minimize the bad.

00:44:27.024 --> 00:44:30.408
And this, kind of, how do you help people

00:44:30.408 --> 00:44:34.778
with mental illness is
the fundamental question.

00:44:34.778 --> 00:44:38.723
And so, kind of that
notion of what do we know?

00:44:38.723 --> 00:44:39.642
How do we know what we know?

00:44:39.642 --> 00:44:40.621
What don't we know?

00:44:40.621 --> 00:44:42.325
Why don't we know that?

00:44:42.325 --> 00:44:45.802
But, you know, my first assumption
is the brain's involved.

00:44:45.802 --> 00:44:46.670
I hope so.

00:44:46.670 --> 00:44:48.725
If it's like the spleen or
something, I'm gonna feel

00:44:48.725 --> 00:44:50.973
like a complete fool down the road.

00:44:50.973 --> 00:44:55.140
But I think, you know, that's
a good reasonable assumption.

00:44:56.718 --> 00:44:59.288
And Professor Jernigan began this journey.

00:44:59.288 --> 00:45:03.014
BJ and I started together
each following down that path

00:45:03.014 --> 00:45:07.097
of looking at the brain
and how the brain changes

00:45:07.974 --> 00:45:11.722
in both typical development
and in illnesses.

00:45:11.722 --> 00:45:14.825
It's kind of a non-creative
design actually.

00:45:14.825 --> 00:45:17.968
But scan kids, you know,
when they're young,

00:45:17.968 --> 00:45:20.870
and follow them as they grow through life.

00:45:20.870 --> 00:45:24.080
See how they're doing at school, at home.

00:45:24.080 --> 00:45:28.233
See what sort of
influences are on the brain

00:45:28.233 --> 00:45:29.893
for good or ill.

00:45:29.893 --> 00:45:34.060
And at the NH, we did about
10,000 scans, half the kids

00:45:36.438 --> 00:45:40.339
healthy, half the kids
with different illnesses.

00:45:40.339 --> 00:45:43.672
And what we've found were, it's nuanced,

00:45:45.060 --> 00:45:46.431
but like, the brain doesn't mature

00:45:46.431 --> 00:45:48.576
by getting bigger and bigger.

00:45:48.576 --> 00:45:51.812
By first grade, it's already
93% of an adult size.

00:45:51.812 --> 00:45:55.227
It matures by becoming more
connected within itself

00:45:55.227 --> 00:45:57.640
and more specialized.

00:45:57.640 --> 00:46:01.632
And this idea of being more connected,

00:46:01.632 --> 00:46:04.494
there's many ways you can approach this,

00:46:04.494 --> 00:46:05.937
but white matter is one of them.

00:46:05.937 --> 00:46:08.571
So this insulating material
that you'll get one

00:46:08.571 --> 00:46:11.882
to two percent more of in
the fourth or fifth decade.

00:46:11.882 --> 00:46:16.049
The brain was able to communicate
amongst itself faster.

00:46:17.081 --> 00:46:18.439
It's not very subtle.

00:46:18.439 --> 00:46:21.875
It's like a 3,000 fold
increase in bandwidth.

00:46:21.875 --> 00:46:25.951
It's, I think, underlies a lot
of the remarkable behaviors

00:46:25.951 --> 00:46:27.201
that we can do.

00:46:28.199 --> 00:46:31.731
But it's not just a matter
of maximizing speed.

00:46:31.731 --> 00:46:33.431
It's all about the timing.

00:46:33.431 --> 00:46:37.381
And so fire together, wire
together, the meaning,

00:46:37.381 --> 00:46:40.616
all the information in these patterns.

00:46:40.616 --> 00:46:42.170
But more and more we're understanding

00:46:42.170 --> 00:46:45.187
that's the progression, and
if we look at different parts

00:46:45.187 --> 00:46:46.977
of the brain like letters of the alphabet,

00:46:46.977 --> 00:46:51.144
as we go from an infant to
child latency, teenagers,

00:46:52.184 --> 00:46:55.182
emerging adulthood that
these letters become words,

00:46:55.182 --> 00:46:56.773
the words become sentences, the sentences,

00:46:56.773 --> 00:46:59.159
you know, paragraphs metaphorically.

00:46:59.159 --> 00:47:02.838
And this all goes up in adolescence.

00:47:02.838 --> 00:47:05.112
The brain almost, no
matter how you measure it,

00:47:05.112 --> 00:47:08.945
whether molecular, EEG,
blood flow, it's just,

00:47:11.490 --> 00:47:13.337
you know, it becomes more connected.

00:47:13.337 --> 00:47:16.076
And this is a kind of
a fresh look in terms

00:47:16.076 --> 00:47:18.412
of this idea of graph theory networks,

00:47:18.412 --> 00:47:20.398
and it gives us a whole new look.

00:47:20.398 --> 00:47:24.355
So for something like
schizophrenia, before we'd be like,

00:47:24.355 --> 00:47:26.238
is this chunk bigger or smaller

00:47:26.238 --> 00:47:28.541
or a different shape or size?

00:47:28.541 --> 00:47:32.766
But looking at the same
MRI scan and the same data

00:47:32.766 --> 00:47:34.879
and looking at how it's interconnected,

00:47:34.879 --> 00:47:38.412
then we can discern old from
young, healthy from ill,

00:47:38.412 --> 00:47:39.863
cause they bring it back.

00:47:39.863 --> 00:47:43.792
Not perfectly, but it's really
exciting for someone like me.

00:47:43.792 --> 00:47:47.057
I can't do the math, but
to be a consumer of it

00:47:47.057 --> 00:47:51.699
in terms of that, by looking
at this connectivity,

00:47:51.699 --> 00:47:56.001
it gives us a whole new
perspective on these illnesses.

00:47:56.001 --> 00:47:58.267
The other process is
the gray matter process.

00:47:58.267 --> 00:48:02.275
And the one, two punch is
over produce and then war

00:48:02.275 --> 00:48:05.185
or fight it out, so it's
how almost all complexity

00:48:05.185 --> 00:48:06.957
in nature arises.

00:48:06.957 --> 00:48:09.876
Engine of evolution, over
produce something non-random

00:48:09.876 --> 00:48:13.464
selection, and it has
great, you know, potential.

00:48:13.464 --> 00:48:15.748
So it's constantly ongoing.

00:48:15.748 --> 00:48:18.049
It's not like you only over
produce during childhood

00:48:18.049 --> 00:48:21.037
and only prune during
adolescence, but we see this

00:48:21.037 --> 00:48:25.204
upside down U type of curve
where, as we specialize,

00:48:26.445 --> 00:48:29.222
the brain actually becomes smaller.

00:48:29.222 --> 00:48:33.140
So after around 10, 11, 12,
your brain doesn't get bigger.

00:48:33.140 --> 00:48:35.880
It gets smaller but leaner,
meaner, more specialized

00:48:35.880 --> 00:48:38.630
based on what is demanding of it.

00:48:39.775 --> 00:48:41.918
But it's not all parts equal.

00:48:41.918 --> 00:48:45.977
The prefrontal cortex involved
in controlling impulses,

00:48:45.977 --> 00:48:49.999
long-range planning, it's
particularly late to settle down.

00:48:49.999 --> 00:48:54.166
Some 25 to 30, and that
combined with the hormonally

00:48:56.816 --> 00:49:00.122
activated puberty activated limbic system,

00:49:00.122 --> 00:49:03.352
the path of rewards,
this imbalance creates

00:49:03.352 --> 00:49:07.519
a lot of the specialness
of teen behavior aspects.

00:49:09.182 --> 00:49:12.188
But again, this is how it should be.

00:49:12.188 --> 00:49:16.130
If the prefrontal cortex was already done,

00:49:16.130 --> 00:49:19.453
like 11 or 12 and stuff, then,
we wouldn't be as adaptable.

00:49:19.453 --> 00:49:22.679
And so I think this is the
tension or the trade off.

00:49:22.679 --> 00:49:26.276
The other place to start in terms of that,

00:49:26.276 --> 00:49:30.228
these illnesses happen at
different times and not perfectly.

00:49:30.228 --> 00:49:32.448
There's always variation, but
Alzheimer's doesn't happen

00:49:32.448 --> 00:49:36.008
when you're three, and autism
doesn't start when you're 60.

00:49:36.008 --> 00:49:38.653
That characteristically,
certain illnesses tend

00:49:38.653 --> 00:49:40.820
to emerge at certain ages.

00:49:42.538 --> 00:49:43.904
And that's puzzling, you know.

00:49:43.904 --> 00:49:44.851
Why is that?

00:49:44.851 --> 00:49:48.353
In terms of, and when you
start looking at this,

00:49:48.353 --> 00:49:50.581
so much happens in adolescence.

00:49:50.581 --> 00:49:51.914
Not a lot, most.

00:49:53.126 --> 00:49:56.815
So up to 75%, and I still
don't know the answer.

00:49:56.815 --> 00:49:59.957
For 25 years, I've been like, why?

00:49:59.957 --> 00:50:03.267
Because the early answer is
oh, teenagers are stressful.

00:50:03.267 --> 00:50:05.311
It's stressful time of life.

00:50:05.311 --> 00:50:07.417
Kids have their parents
killed in front of them

00:50:07.417 --> 00:50:10.076
or a lot are starving to
death in war-torn countries.

00:50:10.076 --> 00:50:14.160
Enormous stresses, but they
don't get schizophrenia.

00:50:14.160 --> 00:50:17.299
And so that never rang true.

00:50:17.299 --> 00:50:18.804
And I still don't know, I
don't know the answer to this.

00:50:18.804 --> 00:50:22.352
Why do things happen when they do?

00:50:22.352 --> 00:50:26.102
And so just one example
is for schizophrenia.

00:50:27.359 --> 00:50:30.054
All of the findings you
see in adult schizophrenia,

00:50:30.054 --> 00:50:32.933
you could predict, what
if typical teen changes

00:50:32.933 --> 00:50:34.016
went too far?

00:50:35.305 --> 00:50:36.326
Is not causal.

00:50:36.326 --> 00:50:37.337
They already had schizophrenia.

00:50:37.337 --> 00:50:40.175
But it sort of, so far without exception

00:50:40.175 --> 00:50:42.629
in terms of both the MRI changes

00:50:42.629 --> 00:50:44.108
but also the molecular changes.

00:50:44.108 --> 00:50:48.213
And so, it's just, this
point, it's intriguing.

00:50:48.213 --> 00:50:51.488
It doesn't help me help
families with schizophrenia.

00:50:51.488 --> 00:50:53.059
But I think these are the kinds of clues

00:50:53.059 --> 00:50:55.726
that we're starting to understand.

00:50:55.726 --> 00:50:58.458
So in the specialization process,

00:50:58.458 --> 00:51:02.625
in typical development, it's
about 7% from ages 12 to 17.

00:51:03.792 --> 00:51:06.687
In schizophrenia, 28%.

00:51:06.687 --> 00:51:10.288
So it's not subtle, you
know, a four fold difference.

00:51:10.288 --> 00:51:14.338
And so understanding
the typical development,

00:51:14.338 --> 00:51:17.328
I think is key, but about
half of what I deal with

00:51:17.328 --> 00:51:20.046
as an illness, isn't an illness, right.

00:51:20.046 --> 00:51:21.544
Pregnancy is not an illness.

00:51:21.544 --> 00:51:24.238
But it's a big deal, right.

00:51:24.238 --> 00:51:27.435
Relationships, car accidents,
incarceration, you know,

00:51:27.435 --> 00:51:29.770
life decisions, this
happens during adolescence.

00:51:29.770 --> 00:51:33.248
And it's frustrating,
you know, as a physician,

00:51:33.248 --> 00:51:35.636
it's like there's no
insurance forms to check

00:51:35.636 --> 00:51:37.621
in terms of for these very real issues

00:51:37.621 --> 00:51:39.905
that aren't an illness.

00:51:39.905 --> 00:51:42.836
And this kind of notion,
is the glass half empty

00:51:42.836 --> 00:51:44.707
or half full?

00:51:44.707 --> 00:51:48.604
Because this changeability
could be a great opportunity

00:51:48.604 --> 00:51:51.710
making it even more tragic
that we aren't recognizing

00:51:51.710 --> 00:51:53.916
the illnesses when they occur.

00:51:53.916 --> 00:51:58.505
And my final sort of analogy
is to use Michelangelo

00:51:58.505 --> 00:52:00.952
in terms of this is a very
famous painting of his

00:52:00.952 --> 00:52:04.447
that by design should look like a brain,

00:52:04.447 --> 00:52:06.531
a cross-section of the brain.

00:52:06.531 --> 00:52:09.341
Yeah, he wrote about it himself and stuff,

00:52:09.341 --> 00:52:11.664
and it's sometimes called
the original synapse.

00:52:11.664 --> 00:52:12.497
You know?

00:52:12.497 --> 00:52:14.250
(audience laughs)

00:52:14.250 --> 00:52:16.115
A little neuroscience humor.

00:52:16.115 --> 00:52:17.826
But it's not like that.

00:52:17.826 --> 00:52:21.993
It's much more like his other
expression of art, sculpting.

00:52:23.583 --> 00:52:27.750
And we start with this block
of marble and life experiences.

00:52:29.105 --> 00:52:31.325
So then, we eliminate parts.

00:52:31.325 --> 00:52:34.400
So me might be born with
different chunks of marble,

00:52:34.400 --> 00:52:39.011
from sizes, from genetics,
but within each if we knew

00:52:39.011 --> 00:52:42.196
what we were doing, if we
could guide this process,

00:52:42.196 --> 00:52:44.277
you know, there's masterpieces.

00:52:44.277 --> 00:52:47.616
And, you know, in I
think almost everybody.

00:52:47.616 --> 00:52:52.244
And we don't know very, we
don't know what we're doing yet

00:52:52.244 --> 00:52:56.245
very well, and it's like, most
of the illnesses emerging,

00:52:56.245 --> 00:52:58.720
less than one and a half
percent of the funding

00:52:58.720 --> 00:53:00.294
has been adolescence.

00:53:00.294 --> 00:53:04.585
Until now, finally, now,
we have this project

00:53:04.585 --> 00:53:08.752
that for the first time is
going to really do this right.

00:53:11.248 --> 00:53:14.805
11, 12,000 or, you know, kids, 19 sites

00:53:14.805 --> 00:53:18.638
across the country to
understand what matters.

00:53:20.143 --> 00:53:22.856
How does the brain grow
in health and illness?

00:53:22.856 --> 00:53:25.952
Looking at, you know, everything
we can think of frankly,

00:53:25.952 --> 00:53:28.619
in terms of, influences on this.

00:53:29.848 --> 00:53:33.778
I'm gonna brag for San
Diego a bit in terms of

00:53:33.778 --> 00:53:36.405
there's these 19 sites across the country,

00:53:36.405 --> 00:53:39.663
but the coordinating center
for the quantitative core

00:53:39.663 --> 00:53:43.940
and the neuropsych core
coordinating all the centers

00:53:43.940 --> 00:53:45.975
are both here in San Diego as well.

00:53:45.975 --> 00:53:50.024
What a good deal for us in
terms of the opportunities

00:53:50.024 --> 00:53:52.607
to try to understand, you know,

00:53:53.447 --> 00:53:55.870
what matters in teen's lives.

00:53:55.870 --> 00:53:59.244
And so the technology is a big part of it.

00:53:59.244 --> 00:54:01.556
How can we get a better sense of internal

00:54:01.556 --> 00:54:04.586
and external environment with the sensors,

00:54:04.586 --> 00:54:08.490
with devices they're already
using, they're already wearing

00:54:08.490 --> 00:54:10.249
cause this is the crossroads in right,

00:54:10.249 --> 00:54:13.529
this is where people, you
know, make big decisions

00:54:13.529 --> 00:54:16.336
about their direction in life.

00:54:16.336 --> 00:54:19.232
And there's this kind of notion that teens

00:54:19.232 --> 00:54:22.236
are messed up and they're
misguided and stuff,

00:54:22.236 --> 00:54:23.908
and it's dangerous.

00:54:23.908 --> 00:54:26.668
I feel bad that I've, cause I've...

00:54:26.668 --> 00:54:28.405
(audience laughs)

00:54:28.405 --> 00:54:30.734
Oh, I see, people, I don't know.

00:54:30.734 --> 00:54:33.320
So this is in the crossroads.

00:54:33.320 --> 00:54:35.704
And what happens is even teens themselves

00:54:35.704 --> 00:54:37.340
buy into this, right.

00:54:37.340 --> 00:54:39.247
Like stereotype threat and stuff.

00:54:39.247 --> 00:54:42.170
If you think that you're not
capable and stuff like that.

00:54:42.170 --> 00:54:43.063
It matters.

00:54:43.063 --> 00:54:44.721
Most teens do well.

00:54:44.721 --> 00:54:45.943
You know, they'll get through this.

00:54:45.943 --> 00:54:46.819
They'll do well.

00:54:46.819 --> 00:54:49.139
But I think we do a
disservice by, you know,

00:54:49.139 --> 00:54:52.878
selling them short, and
I think that, you know,

00:54:52.878 --> 00:54:55.710
we really need to recognize
the huge upsides of this.

00:54:55.710 --> 00:54:57.525
Much more than the downsides.

00:54:57.525 --> 00:55:00.461
That if we can figure out what
we're doing, what matters,

00:55:00.461 --> 00:55:02.963
we can really make a big difference.

00:55:02.963 --> 00:55:03.960
Thanks.

00:55:03.960 --> 00:55:04.793
(audience applauds)

00:55:04.793 --> 00:55:07.876
(light upbeat music)

